 of Thailand -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen political geography changes, how do reorganized or newly formed states justify their rule and create a sense of shared history for their people? Often, the essays in Selective Remembrances reveal, they turn to archaeology, employing the field and its findings to develop nationalistic feelings and forge legitimate distinctive national identities. Examining such relatively new or reconfigured nation-states as Iran, Iraq, Turkey, Israel, Russia, Ukraine, India, and Thailand, Selective Remembrances shows how states invoke the remote past to extol the glories of specific peoples or prove claims to ancestral homelands. Religion has long played a key role in such efforts, and the contributors take care to demonstrate the tendency of many people, including archaeologists themselves, to view the world through a religious lens—which can be exploited by new regimes to suppress objective study of the past and justify contemporary political actions. The wide geographic and intellectual range of the essays in Selective Remembrances will make it a seminal text for archaeologists and historians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArchaeology and state. 0aArchaeology. 0aHistoriography. 0aHistory. 0aMemory. 0aNationalism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aarchaeology, archaeologists, archaeological, anthropology, anthropological, construction, commemoration, consecration, nation, memory, remembering, history, historical, sociology, sociological, sociologists, anthropologists, political geography, politics, national identities, iran, iraq, turkey, israel, russia, ukraine, india, thailand, religion, religious, case study, historiography, authenticity, colonialism, nationa